        lessonNotes: '<h4>Citizenship and Civic Rights</h4><p><strong>Citizenship</strong> is the legal status of being a member of a country, entitling an individual to enjoy rights and perform duties. In West African nations, citizenship can be acquired by <strong>birth</strong>, <strong>descent</strong>, <strong>registration</strong>, or <strong>naturalization</strong>. Every citizen is entitled to fundamental civil liberties including freedom of speech, freedom of movement, and the right to vote.</p><p><strong>Civic rights</strong> are the rights guaranteed to citizens by the constitution and laws of the state. These include the right to a fair trial, the right to education, and the right to participate in governance. The <strong>constitution</strong> is the supreme law of the land and protects these rights from infringement by the government or other individuals.</p><p>Citizens also have corresponding <strong>civic duties</strong> such as paying taxes, obeying the law, participating in elections, and defending the nation. The balance between rights and responsibilities is essential to a functioning democratic society. Understanding one\'s rights helps citizens hold their governments accountable and contribute meaningfully to national development.</p>',
