        icon: '\u{1F5F3}',
        lessonNotes: '<h4>Democratic Governance and Political Participation</h4><p><strong>Democracy</strong> is a system of government in which power is vested in the people, who exercise it directly or through freely elected representatives. The word comes from the Greek words <strong>demos</strong> (people) and <strong>kratos</strong> (rule). Key principles of democracy include the rule of the majority, respect for minority rights, separation of powers, periodic free and fair elections, and the protection of fundamental human rights.</p><p>There are two main types of democracy: <strong>direct democracy</strong>, in which citizens vote directly on laws and policies (as practiced in ancient Athens), and <strong>representative (indirect) democracy</strong>, in which citizens elect representatives to make decisions on their behalf. Most modern nations, including those in West Africa, practice representative democracy. Important features include a multi-party system, an independent judiciary, a free press, and accountable government institutions.</p><p><strong>Political participation</strong> refers to the various ways citizens engage with the political process. This includes voting in elections, joining political parties, contacting elected officials, running for office, attending public meetings, and participating in peaceful protests. High levels of political participation strengthen democracy and ensure that government policies reflect the will of the people. <strong>Voter apathy</strong>, the lack of interest in voting, is a major challenge to democratic governance in many West African countries.</p>',
